<<<<<Basic Flags>>>>> A handful of flags cover almost everything you'll need day to day:

        --bind src:dst        Make a folder on your machine visible inside the
                              container at path dst. This is how the container
                              sees your code, data, and writes results (and the
                              MLflow DB/artifacts) back out. Repeat the flag to
                              bind more than one folder:
                                --bind /my/code:/code --bind /my/output:/output

        --env KEY=VALUE       Set an environment variable inside the container
                              for this run only, e.g. --env OMP_NUM_THREADS=4

        (This container is CPU-only, so --nv / --rocm are not needed. For the
        full list of options, see: apptainer help exec)

<<<<</Basic Flags>>>>>
========================================================================================
<<<<<Modes>>>>> There are four ways to use this container: run it plainly, exec a specific command, shell in interactively, or launch it as a background instance.

        RUN — start a built-in mode
        --------------------------------
        Launches a pre-built mode that ships with the container. You don't
        point it at a script — you just pick the mode and it starts. The mode
        name goes at the end of the command.

          apptainer run --bind /my/code:/code --bind /my/output:/output container.sif <mode>

          jupyter (default)     JupyterLab, for interactive notebooks —
                                `import mlflow` works out of the box

          mlflow                MLflow tracking server + UI only, nothing else

          jupyter+mlflow        Both at once — server in the background,
                                JupyterLab in the foreground

        Running with no mode at all uses the default (jupyter). To be
        explicit, always pass the mode you want.

        EXEC — run your own commands and scripts
        --------------------------------
        Runs a single command, or one of your own scripts (like train.py),
        inside the container. This is how you do actual work — bind in your
        code and data, set any env vars you need, and point exec at what to run.

          apptainer exec --bind /my/code:/code --bind /my/data:/data \
            --bind /my/output:/output container.sif python /code/train.py

          # Inspect MLflow runs without starting the full server
          apptainer exec --bind /my/output:/output container.sif mlflow runs list

          # Jupyter Lab, reachable via SSH tunnel
          apptainer exec --bind /my/code:/code container.sif \
            jupyter lab --ip=0.0.0.0 --no-browser --port=8888
          # then from your laptop:
          ssh -L 8888:<compute-node>:8888 <you>@<login-node>
          # open http://localhost:8888

          # MLflow UI, same idea, tunnel the tracking port instead
          apptainer exec --bind /my/output:/output container.sif \
            mlflow server --backend-store-uri sqlite:////output/mlflow.db \
            --default-artifact-root /output/artifacts --host 0.0.0.0 --port 5000
          # then: ssh -L 5000:<compute-node>:5000 <you>@<login-node>
          # open http://localhost:5000

        SHELL — drop into an interactive prompt
        --------------------------------
        Starts an interactive shell inside the container. No command runs
        automatically — useful for inspecting the environment, checking
        installed packages, or running things manually.

          apptainer shell --bind /my/code:/code --bind /my/output:/output container.sif
          # Type `exit` to leave.

        INSTANCE — run the container as a persistent background service
        --------------------------------
        Starts the container detached, so it keeps running (e.g. a shared
        MLflow tracking server) after you disconnect.

          apptainer instance start --bind /my/output:/output \
            container.sif mlflow-tracker

          apptainer exec instance://mlflow-tracker mlflow runs list

          apptainer instance list
          apptainer instance stop mlflow-tracker

<<<<</Modes>>>>>
========================================================================================
<<<<<Installing Extra Packages>>>>> You can `pip install` something new right inside a running container — it will work for that session. But the container filesystem resets on every fresh run, so anything you installed is gone next time, unless you use an overlay or a persistent venv in $HOME:

        apptainer overlay create --size 1024 overlay.img
        apptainer shell --overlay overlay.img --bind /my/code:/code container.sif
        pip install <package>

        Reuse the same overlay.img next time to see the package again.

        For a longer-term setup instead, create a venv in $HOME with
        --system-site-packages so the base stack stays visible, and unset
        PIP_CONSTRAINT to release the base image's package lock. See
        `apptainer run-help container.sif` for the full walkthrough.

<<<<</Installing Extra Packages>>>>>
========================================================================================
<<<<<More Help & Testing>>>>> For the full list of built-in modes, flags, and usage details:

